			    STPJS 266</div>
  <p class="cont">Enoch was righteous enough to come into the presence of God, and walk with him,<span class="footRef">1</span> he must have
  become so by keeping his commandments,<span class="footRef">2</span> and so of every righteous person,<span class="footRef">3</span> whether it was Noah,
  a preacher of righteousness;<span class="footRef">4</span> Abraham, the father of the faithful;<span class="footRef">5</span> Jacob, the prevailer with God;<span class="footRef">6</span>
  Moses, the man who wrote of Christ,<span class="footRef">7</span> and brought forth the law by commandment,<span class="footRef">8</span> as a
  schoolmaster to bring men to Christ,<span class="footRef">9</span> or whether it was Jesus Christ himself, who had no need of
  repentance,<span class="footRef">10</span> having no sin,<span class="footRef">11</span> according to his solemn declaration to John:&mdash;now let me be
  baptized:<span class="footRef">12</span> for no man can enter the kingdom without obeying this ordinance:<span class="footRef">13</span> for thus it becometh
  us to fulfil ALL RIGHTEOUSNESS.<span class="footRef">14</span> Surely, then, if it became John and Jesus Christ, the Savior,
  to fulfil all righteousness to be baptized&mdash;so surely, then, it will become every other person that
  seeks the kingdom of heaven to go and do likewise;<span class="footRef">15</span> for he is the door, and if any person climbs up
  any other way, the same is a thief and a robber!<span class="footRef">16</span></p>
  <div class="topic">Baptism Required in All Ages</div>
  <p class="std">In the former ages of the world, before the Savior came in the flesh,<span class="footRef">17</span> &ldquo;the saints&rdquo;<span class="footRef">18</span> were
  baptized<span class="footRef">19</span> in the name of Jesus Christ to come,<span class="footRef">20</span> because there never was any other name whereby
  men could be saved;<span class="footRef">21</span> and after he came in the flesh and was crucified, then the saints were baptized
  in the name of Jesus Christ,<span class="footRef">22</span> crucified, risen from the dead<span class="footRef">23</span> and ascended into heaven,<span class="footRef">24</span> that they
  might be buried in baptism like him,<span class="footRef">25</span> and be raised in glory like him,<span class="footRef">26</span> that as there was but one
  Lord, one faith, one baptism,<span class="footRef">27</span> and one God and father of us all,<span class="footRef">28</span> even so there was but one door<span class="footRef">29</span>
  to the mansions of bliss.<span class="footRef">30</span> Amen. (Sept. 1, 1842.) T&amp;S 3:902–905.</p>
  <div class="topic">&ldquo;FACTS ARE STUBBORN THINGS&rdquo;</div>
  <div class="topic">Greatness of the Jaredites and Nephites</div>
  <p class="std">From an extract from &ldquo;Stephen&rsquo;s Incidents of Travel in Central America,&rdquo; it will be seen that the
  proof of the Nephites and Lamanites dwelling on this continent, according to the account in the
  Book of Mormon, is developing itself in a more satisfactory way than the most sanguine believer
  in that revelation could have anticipated. It certainly affords us a gratification that the world of
  mankind does not enjoy, to give publicity</p>
